A Practical Introduction for Future Full-Stack Developers
- HTML stands for HyperText Markup Language.
- It is NOT a programming language
- It's the standard language used to create web pages.
- It structures content with elements like headings, paragraphs,
- Every website you visit uses HTML in some form.
The skeleton of a simple HTML document
How tags open, close, or self-close
- These elements have opening and closing tags.
- The closing tag has a / in it.
How tags open, close, or self-close
Some elements don’t wrap content—they close themselves.
HTML tags must be closed in the correct order
When you open tags inside other tags, you must close the inner tags

- <html> Root element of the HTML document.
- <body> Contains all the visible page content.
- <title> Sets the title in the browser tab.
- <meta> Defines metadata like character set, SEO stuff, and so on.
- <header> Introductory content or navigation (often at the top).
- <section> Thematic grouping of content, like a chapter or section.
- <article> A self-contained piece of content (e.g., blog post).
- <aside> Content related to the main page (e.g., sidebar).
- <footer> Footer for a section or the whole page.
- <main> The main content of the page (only one per page).
- <figure> Container for media (like images) with optional caption.
- <a> Hyperlink to another page or resource.
- Embeds an image. Requires src and alt.
- <iframe> Embeds another page or document (like a YouTube
- <noscript> Content shown if JavaScript is disabled.
- <canvas> Drawing surface for graphics via JavaScript.

text.tspan: Writing notes for yourself and other developers
Text between <!-- and --> are ignored by the browser and useful
for you to add notes to the code.
Writing notes for yourself and other developers
Comments can be used for many purposes:
- Marking where a section begins or ends
- Temporarily disable part of the code or hide part of the page
- Don't overuse comments for obvious things.
- Avoid leaving sensitive information in comments.
